    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-05-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="10" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d10">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Tripp</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-05-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 9,
                                1895</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 141.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose for your information a copy of a
                            note from the Austro-Hungarian minister of the 1st instant,<note n="1" xml:id="d10fn1">See <ref target="#pg_8">page 8</ref>.</note> and of
                            the Department’s reply of the 8th,<note n="2" xml:id="d10fn2">See <ref target="#pg_9">page 9</ref>.</note> in regard to his inquiry
                            concerning the case of Frederick Hillebrandt, to whom a passport, No.
                            3897, was issued August 7, 1893. I add, also, a copy of Mr.
                            Hillebrandt’s application of August 4, 1893, as well as a copy of an
                            instruction, No. 19, of November 26, 1892,<note n="3" xml:id="d10fn3">Printed in <ref target="frus1892#pg_530">Foreign Relations, 1892,
                                    p. 530</ref>.</note> to the United States minister at St.
                            Petersburg, in a somewhat similar case, and which emphasizes the point
                            that this Government expects its passports to be accepted abroad as
                            prima facie evidence of citizenship. When their validity is assailed by
                            competent proof, the hearty cooperation of this Government may be relied
                            upon to investigate and determine the disputed point.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin F. Uhl</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
